In TypeScript, you can use the following method to tell the type system that you know the value will only have one type:

```typescript
function foo(arg: number): number {
  // do something
}
```

Here, you are telling the type system that `arg` is a number and that it will only have one value, so you can use it as a number. This is known as a "known return value type." You can also use the `typeof` operator to get the actual type of `arg`:

```typesscript
function foo(arg: string): typeof arg {
  // do something
}
```

This will ensure that `arg` has the type of the string value, even if it was originally passed in as a number.

Here is a sample code for counting the number of occurrences of a specific word in a text file using C++:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <cstring>

int main() {
    // Open the file for reading
    std::ifstream infile("input_file.txt");
    if (!infile) {
        std::cout << "Error opening input file" << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }

    // Declare a variable to store the number of occurrences of the word
    int word_count = 0;
    std::string line;
    while (getline(infile, line)) {
        // Count the number of occurrences of the word in the line
        size_t found = line.find(std::string("word_to_search"));
        if (found != std::string::npos) {
            word_count++;
        }
    }
    std::cout << "Word \"word_to_search\" occurs " << word_count << " times in the file." << std::endl;
}
